BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 600.70 Tm (A quick reminder of scaling from last time. Vertical scaling - scale up - is making one machine) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 585.50 Tm (more powerful; simple, but it has a ceiling and gets expensive. Horizontal scaling - scale out - is) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 570.30 Tm (adding more machines, each running a copy; no ceiling, cost-effective, and fault-tolerant.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 550.10 Tm (Now here is the catch that sets up everything today. When you scale horizontally, you end up with) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 534.90 Tm (multiple copies of the same service - for example, our Student service running on three different) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 519.70 Tm (ports at once. And that creates two brand-new headaches. First - how does anyone know all those) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 504.50 Tm (addresses? Copies come and go, on changing ports. You cannot just hard-code an address. And) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 489.30 Tm (second - how do we spread the traffic evenly across all those copies?) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 469.10 Tm (Hold those two questions in your head. Because the next two patterns - a Service Registry and an) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 453.90 Tm (API Gateway - are precisely the answers. One solves 'where is everything', the other solves 'share) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 438.70 Tm (the traffic'. Everything today flows from this slide.) Tj ET
0.040 0.520 1.000 rg 58.00 423.50 3.00 199.20 re f
