0.040 0.520 1.000 rg 58.00 729.00 496.00 1.40 re f
BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.420 0.420 0.460 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 713.00 Tm (ON SCREEN) Tj ET
BT /F1 10.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 697.00 Tm (A request flowing through Gateway, Order MS, Inventory MS, Payment MS, and a Zipkin-style timing) Tj ET
BT /F1 10.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 683.50 Tm (breakdown.) Tj ET
0.720 0.720 0.760 rg 58.00 670.00 3.00 49.00 re f
BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.040 0.340 0.780 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 659.00 Tm (SAY \(read this aloud\)) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 643.00 Tm (Pattern four - distributed tracing. Concept only, but really important to understand. Here is the) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 627.80 Tm (problem it solves. In a microservices system, one user request might travel through five different) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 612.60 Tm (services to get its job done. Now suppose the whole thing feels slow. Which service is the culprit?) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 597.40 Tm (In a monolith you could just check one log. But here the request is scattered across five separate) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 582.20 Tm (programs. How do you follow it?) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 562.00 Tm (Distributed tracing is the answer. Every incoming request is given a unique trace ID - like a) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 546.80 Tm (tracking number on a parcel. That same ID is passed along to every service the request touches.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 531.60 Tm (Each service logs its work with that ID. Then a tool called Zipkin gathers all the logs that share that) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 516.40 Tm (ID and stitches them into one timeline.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 496.20 Tm (Look at the breakdown on screen - it shows how long each service took, and immediately you can) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 481.00 Tm (see the slow one lit up. So just like tracking a parcel across multiple delivery hubs, you can see) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 465.80 Tm (exactly where the request spent its time, and where it got stuck. The tools are Micrometer and) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 450.60 Tm (Zipkin. We are not building it today, but the moment you have more than two services, you will be) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 435.40 Tm (grateful it exists.) Tj ET
0.040 0.520 1.000 rg 58.00 420.20 3.00 244.80 re f
BT /F2 15.00 Tf 0.100 0.100 0.120 rg 1 0 0 1 58.00 401.20 Tm (Slide 12 - Circuit Breaker) Tj ET
0.040 0.520 1.000 rg 58.00 384.20 496.00 1.40 re f
BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.420 0.420 0.460 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 368.20 Tm (ON SCREEN) Tj ET
BT /F1 10.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 352.20 Tm (A three-state diagram: CLOSED, OPEN, HALF-OPEN, and the transitions between them.) Tj ET
0.720 0.720 0.760 rg 58.00 338.70 3.00 35.50 re f
BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.040 0.340 0.780 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 327.70 Tm (SAY \(read this aloud\)) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 311.70 Tm (Pattern five - the circuit breaker. Concept only, and it borrows its name from the electrical switch in) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 296.50 Tm (your home. Here is the problem. Suppose service A keeps calling service B, but service B has) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 281.30 Tm (crashed. If A keeps hammering away at a dead B, it wastes resources, piles up, and the failure) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 266.10 Tm (can spread - one dead service drags down others. We call that a cascading failure.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 245.90 Tm (A circuit breaker prevents this, with three states - follow the diagram. CLOSED is normal - calls) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 230.70 Tm (flow through, and it quietly counts failures. If too many calls fail, it trips to OPEN - and now, instead) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 215.50 Tm (of hammering the dead service, it instantly returns a fallback, like 'sorry, try again later'. No more) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 200.30 Tm (pointless calls. Then, after a short wait, it goes HALF-OPEN - it cautiously lets one test call) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 185.10 Tm (through. If that works, great, back to CLOSED, normal service. If it fails, back to OPEN, keep) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 169.90 Tm (waiting.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 149.70 Tm (It is exactly like the breaker in your house - when there is a problem, it trips to protect the system,) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 134.50 Tm (and then you carefully check whether it is safe to switch back on. The Spring tool for this is called) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 119.30 Tm (Resilience4j. Not building it today, but a lovely concept to carry with you.) Tj ET
0.040 0.520 1.000 rg 58.00 104.10 3.00 229.60 re f
0.800 0.800 0.840 rg 58.00 44.00 496.00 0.80 re f
